<font color="#FF0000">RESPONSE TO JOE</font><br>
<tt>Mon Jun  2  5:28:21 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
That is a good question, Joe.<br><br>
In my own experience, we &quot;questioned&quot; several orders and SOP's.<br><br>
One actual refusal comes to mind involving mechanical ambushes. &quot;Mechanicals&quot; involved setting up claymore mines on trails. These were placed at dusk, when there was still ample daylight, and picked up the following morning. Trip wires and PRC25 radio batteries were attached to the claymores. These were EXTREMELY dangerous to work with. It is impossible to overemphasize the danger associated with handling these devices. If I recall they were against the Geneva Convention.<br><br>
We had humped all day long and were late getting into our night defensive position. The men were very tired - exhausted is more like it. We had foxholes to dig along with  the other chores that went with setting up a position.<br><br>
One of our officers wanted us to go out and set up these mechanical ambushes in the dark! Can you imagine retrieving them the next morning?<br><br>
Several of us got together and confronted the officer and pretty much *implied* that if he wanted the mechanicals set up, then he was the man that should do it. He backed down. I feel that had he not backed down, we wouldn't have either. This is the closest that I recall ever refusing an order.<br><br>
&quot;Circumventing&quot; them was commonplace - even among the officers who used their own discretion when orders came down from the Battalion.
